The paper's focus on combinatorial objects and their canonization algorithms aligns well with this category. The second likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which covers the design and analysis of algorithms for various computational problems. The paper's emphasis on algorithm design and analysis makes it relevant to this category. The third likely category is cs.CG (Computational Geometry), which deals with algorithms and data structures for geometric problems. Although the paper does not explicitly deal with geometric objects, its focus on combinatorial structures makes it relevant to this category. The fourth likely category is cs.CC (Computational Complexity), which covers the study of the intrinsic difficulty of computational problems. The paper's emphasis on asymptotic running time analysis makes it relevant to this category. The fifth likely category is cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science), which covers the use of logic and formal methods in computer science. Although the paper does not explicitly deal with logic, its focus on combinatorial structures and their properties aligns well with this category.
